-- BHP, Crown, Transurban, James Hardie: Australian Stock Preview
-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a   a n d   M o n a m i   Y u i
-- 2010-10-14T21:56:02Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-14/bhp-crown-gujarat-transurban-james-hardie-australian-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed. All prices are
from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in December
advanced 0.2 percent to 4,700 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The
 Bank of New York Australia ADR Index  rose 1 percent. The  S&P/ASX
200 Index  rose 1.7 percent to 4,699.10.  Gold producers: Gold climbed to a record for a second day
as a weaker dollar spurred demand for an alternative investment.
Gold futures for December delivery added 0.5 percent to close at
$1,377.60 an ounce at 1:50 p.m. in New York,  Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s largest gold
producer, climbed 3.3 percent to A$42.52.  St. Barbara Ltd.  (SBM
AU) surged 7.2 percent to 44.5 Australian cents.  BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BHP AU) and  Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU):
German regulators objected to BHP and Rio’s proposed iron-ore
joint venture after Japanese authorities told the world’s
largest and third-largest mining companies their plan may break
the law. BHP shares rose 2.1 percent to A$41.66. Rio’s jumped
4.4 percent to A$82.08.       Crown Ltd.  (CWN AU): Australia’s largest casino operator
said Chairman  James Packer  has increased his stake in the
company. Packer’s Consolidated Press Holdings acquired 22.6
million shares on market for A$201 million ($200 million), Crown
said in a stock-exchange filing. Crown shares were unchanged at
A$8.77.  Gujarat NRE Minerals Ltd.  (GNM AU): The Australian coal
producer was rated “overweight” in new coverage at JPMorgan
Chase & Co. The stock was unchanged at 61 Australian cents.  James Hardie Industries  (JHX AU): The biggest seller of
home siding in the U.S. had its rating cut to “neutral” from
“outperform” by analysts led by  Rohan Gallagher  at Credit
Suisse Group AG. The stock rose 2.5 percent to A$5.70.  Mirvac Group  (MGR AU): The Australian real-estate
investment trust had its rating cut to “neutral” from
“outperform” by analysts led by  Rowena Causley  at Credit
Suisse Group AG. The shares increased 2.7 percent to A$1.33.       Platinum Australia Ltd.  (PLA AU): The owner of mines in
South Africa and Australia was downgraded to “neutral” from
“outperform” at Macquarie Group Ltd. The shares rose 6.5
percent to 57 Australian cents.       Santos Ltd.  (STO AU): Australian Environment Minister  Tony Burke  may delay a decision on granting approval for Santos and
BG Group Plc’s liquefied natural gas projects, the Australian
Financial Review reported in its Street Talk column, without
saying where it got the information. Santos rose 0.9 percent to
A$12.84.       Transurban Group  (TCL AU): The toll-road operator was
downgraded to “neutral” from “outperform” by analysts at
Macquarie Group Ltd. The shares fell 0.4 percent to A$5.17.  To contact the reporter for this story:
